---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
---

<Layout title="Mon projet">

<main class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6 py-20">

<!-- Title -->
<header class="text-center mb-14">

  <h1 class="text-3xl md:text-5xl font-extrabold mb-6 text-gray-700 dark:text-white leading-tight">
    Everyone practices systems engineering… even you!
  </h1>

  <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">
    Have you ever wondered how people organize themselves to design complex objects such as a smartphone,
    a car, a train, or an aircraft?
  </p>

</header>


<!-- Article -->
<article class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 text-lg leading-relaxed space-y-6">

  <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold mt-6">
    What is systems engineering?
  </h2>

  <p>
    Systems engineering is the art of organizing many different elements so that they work together properly throughout their entire life cycle.
  </p>

  <p>
    Imagine having to create and operate a subway line: you need to manage trains, tracks, electricity, software, maintenance teams, safety rules, passenger information, budgets, and much more.
  </p>

  <p>
    Systems engineering consists of thinking about all these aspects simultaneously, breaking the problem down into understandable parts, and then ensuring that all these elements fit together correctly and continue to work together over time.
  </p>


  <h3 class="text-xl md:text-2xl font-semibold mt-10">
    In practice, a systems engineer:
  </h3>

  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">

    <li>
      Clarifies the real needs of the stakeholders involved (users, customers, authorities, etc.).
    </li>

    <li>
      Imagines several possible solutions, compares their advantages and disadvantages, and chooses the one that best fits the constraints (cost, deadlines, safety, environment, etc.).
    </li>

    <li>
      Coordinates specialists (electronics, mechanics, software, organization, etc.) so that their components integrate without conflict.
    </li>

    <li>
      Verifies throughout the project that the final system truly meets the requirements and remains reliable over time.
    </li>

  </ul>


  <h3 class="text-xl md:text-2xl font-semibold mt-10">
    Everyday life examples:
  </h3>

  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-3">

    <li>
      <strong>Organizing a wedding:</strong>
      budget, location, catering, entertainment, guests, timing, unexpected events…  
      The systems engineer would be the wedding planner who anticipates interactions and ensures everything works smoothly on the big day.
    </li>

    <li>
      <strong>A football team:</strong>
      players, tactics, coach, equipment, physical condition, opponents…  
      The coach plays this role by aligning everyone's skills to ensure fluid teamwork.
    </li>

  </ul>

  <h3>
    In summary, long before becoming a profession, systems engineering is above all a concept, a way of thinking to provide solutions to specific needs.
  </h3>

</article>


  <!-- Bouton retour -->
  <div class="text-center mt-16">

    <a
      href="/"
      class="inline-block bg-blue-600 text-white font-semibold px-6 py-3 rounded-lg shadow-md hover:bg-blue-700 transition-colors duration-300"
    >
      ← Retour à l'accueil
    </a>

  </div>

</main>

</Layout>